05344nam a22007575i 9781487584689DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191991onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875846897 a10.3138/97814875846892doi  a(DE-B1597)527887  a(OCoLC)1114794683  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aPQ3917.Q3bS6313 1991 7aSOC0320002bisacsh04a840.9/9287/0971409042211 aSmart, Patricia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWriting in the Father's House :bThe Emergence of the Feminine in the Quebec Literary Tradition /cPatricia Smart. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©1991  a1 online resource (316 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- tAuthor's note on the English translation -- tIntroduction: Traces of a murder -- t1. Angéline de Montbrun or the fall into writing -- t2. Alphonsine Moisan's subversion: The voice of the repressed feminine in the novel of the land -- t3. Opening the house to the Other: The novels of Germaine Guèvremont -- t4. The defeated son and the rebellious daughter: The poetry of Saint-Denys Garneau and Anne Hébert -- t5. When the voices of resistance become political: The Tin Flute or realism in the feminine -- t6. The corpse under the foundations of the house: Violence to women in the contemporary Quebec novel -- t7. What Oedipus sees: Hamlet's Twin and the impasse of 'his story' -- t8. Reclaiming Electra: The writing of France Théoret -- tConclusion -- tNOTES -- tWORKS CITED -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThose who follow current trends in Canadian literature are aware that many of its most exciting and challenging new formats are coming from women writers of Quebec. Patricia Smart studies the historical roots of this development in her study of gender differences in Quebec literature. She offers a feminist perspective on 100 years of writing by both women and men, and argues that it is the women who have modified or subverted the traditions. This new work is her own translation of her study that won the 1988 Governor General's Award for Non-Fiction, Ecrire dans la maison du père: L'émergence du féminin dans la tradition littéraire du Québec. Smart begins with a feminist reading of Laure Conan's Angéline de Montbrun, the only major novel written by a woman in nineteenth-century Quebec, and moves on to close readings of other classic works, from the novel of the land to postmodern and feminist works of the present era. The Quebec literary tradition is not only 'his story' of the national dilemma. There is another telling, Smart concludes, in a different voice, from a different perspective, by women writers and by female characters in the works by men. Smart proposes a radically new interpretation of Quebec literature, one that includes that voice, that other perspective. For when they are listened to on their own terms, and not according to criteria based on men's writing practices, the voices of women writers and characters point to a way out of the female tradition of alienation and violence and to the possibility of a habitable future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aFrench-Canadian literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aFrench-Canadian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFrench-Canadian literaturezQuébec (Province)xHistory and criticism. 0aFrench-Canadian literaturezQuébec (Province)xHistory and criticism. 0aSex differences (Psychology) in literature. 0aWomen and literaturezQuébec (Province). 0aWomen and literaturezQuébec (Province). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook packa